{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}} {{Use British English|date=December 2013}} '''Alfred William Brian Simpson''', [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (Hon.), [[Justice of the Peace|JP]], [[British Academy#Fellowship|FBA]] (17 August 1931<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.airecentre.org/news.php/15/professor-a.w.-brian-simpson-17th-august-1931-10th-january-2011|title=Professor A.W. Brian Simpson : 17th August 1931- 10th January… · News · The AIRE Centre|work=airecentre.org|accessdate=17 January 2011}}</ref><ref>date & year of birth, full name according to LCNAF [[Cataloging in Publication|CIP]] data</ref> &ndash; 10 January 2011)<ref name="umich" /> usually referred to as '''Brian Simpson''', was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Legal history|legal historian]] and the [[Professors in the United_States#Professor emeritus and emerita|emeritus]] Charles F. and Edith J. Clyne Professor of Law at the [[University of Michigan Law School]].<ref name="umich"> {{cite web|url=http://cgi2.www.law.umich.edu/_FacultyBioPage/facultybiopagenew.asp?ID=237|title=University of Michigan Law School Faculty & Staff|publisher=cgi2.www.law.umich.edu|accessdate=2010-01-06|last=|first=}}</ref>
Born in [[Kendal]], [[Cumbria]], Simpson was educated at [[Oakham School]] and [[The Queen's College, Oxford]], where he took a First in Law.
He was a fellow and tutor of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]] from 1955-1973, before various professorships at the Universities of [[University of Kent|Kent]] (1975-1983), [[University of Chicago|Chicago]], [[University of Michigan|Michigan]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] and [[University of Toronto|Toronto]]. As a result of [[National Service in the United Kingdom|National Service]] with the [[Nigeria Regiment]], he retained an interest in Africa, and was Dean of the Faculty of Law of the [[University of Ghana]] in 1968-69.<ref name="whoswho">http://www.ukwhoswho.com/search/quick?quicksearch=simpson+brian{{paywall}}</ref>
His most serious works of legal history were a ''History of the Land Law'' (2nd Edition, 1986) and a ''History of the Law of Contract'' (1975), but he is best remembered for his ''Cannibalism and the Common Law'' (1984) and ''Leading Cases in Common Law'' (1995). At the end of his career he also wrote two works on twentieth century human rights: ''In the Highest Degree Odious: Detention without Trial in Wartime Britain'' (1992) and ''Human Rights and the End of Empire: Britain and the Genesis of the European Convention'' (2001).<ref name="whoswho" />
Simpson returned to an aspect of his own legal education at Oxford in a book published posthumously in September, 2011, ''Reflections on `The Concept of Law,''' delineating the environment in which [[H. L. A. Hart]] had produced the classic of jurisprudence in the setting of Oxford linguistic philosophy. == References == {{Reflist}}
