{{infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL|suppressfields=awards|honorific_suffix={{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FSA}}}}
[[File:Old Ashmolean 2006.JPG|thumb|Silke Ackermann is the Director of the [[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford]] (above).]]
'''Silke M. Ackermann''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA|}} ({{IPA-de|ˈsɪlkə ˈʔakɐman|lang}}) is a German [[museum curator]] and [[history of science|historian of science]] who is currently the Director of the [[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford|Museum of the History of Science]] at [[Oxford University]].
== Education == Ackermann studied History and [[Oriental Languages]] at the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|University of Frankfurt]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.imss.fi.it/news/comunicare/nomi.html | title=Comunicare La Scienza Nei Musei Dal Concetto All'Exhibit | location=Florence, Italy | date=12 April 2002 | accessdate=29 March 2014 }}</ref> After working for the "Regesta Imperii" Project, she wrote an MA thesis on the 13th-century mathematician, astronomer and astrologer [[Michael Scot]] entitled "''Michael Scot: a universal scholar of the 13th century: Sources of his life - Tradition of his works"''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/25458113?style=html&title=Michael%20Scotusein%20Universalgelehrter%20des%2013.%20Jahrhunderts|title=Michael Scotus : ein Universalgelehrter des 13. Jahrhunderts : Quellen zu seinem Leben - Überlieferung seiner Werke {{!}} Copac|last=Ackermann|first=Silke|date=1987|website=copac.jisc.ac.uk|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616045019/https://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/25458113?style%3Dhtml%26title%3DMichael+Scotusein+Universalgelehrter+des+13.+Jahrhunderts|archive-date=2018-06-16|dead-url=yes|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> Ackermann continued this research for her PhD which she presented in 1996, and was later published as a book.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/4152264?style=html&title=Sternstunden%20am%20KaiserhofMichael%20Scotus%20und%20sein%20Buch|title=Sternstunden am Kaiserhof : Michael Scotus und sein Buch von den Bildern und Zeichen des Himmels {{!}} Copac|last=Ackermann|first=Silke|date=2009|website=copac.jisc.ac.uk|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616045030/https://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/4152264?style%3Dhtml%26title%3DSternstunden+am+KaiserhofMichael+Scotus+und+sein+Buch|archive-date=2018-06-16|dead-url=yes|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> During this research, Ackermann studied [[History of Science]] at the Institute for the History of Science within Frankfurt University and acted as an assistant to Prof. [[David A. King (historian)|David King]].
== Career == From 1996, Ackermann was the Curator of European and Islamic [[scientific instrument]]s at the [[British Museum]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/people/silke-ackermann | title=Silke Ackermann | work=| publisher=[[University of Oxford]] | location=UK | date=14 October 2013 | accessdate=29 March 2014 }}</ref> In April 2005 she was elected a fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London|Society of Antiquaries]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sal.org.uk/about-us/fellows-directory/?fs=ackermann|title=Fellows Directory - Society of Antiquaries|website=www.sal.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> In 2012, Ackermann took up a professorship at the University of Applied Sciences [[:de:Baltic College|Baltic College]] in [[Schwerin]], Germany, where she was later appointed president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dr-gerald-wetzel.de/assets/2012-12-21bcnews.pdf|title=Prof. Dr. Ackermann wird neue prädidentin|last=|first=|date=July 2017|work=BCnews|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nordic-market.de/news/6660/prof_dr_silke_ackermann_neue_praesidentin_am_baltic_college.htm|title=Prof. Dr. Silke Ackermann neue Präsidentin am Baltic College - Wissenschaft - Nordic Market|website=www.nordic-market.de|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref><ref name="oxford-times">{{cite news| url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/10719649.History_of_Science___s_leader_is_appointed/?ref=rss | title=History of Science’s leader is appointed | work=[[The Oxford Times]] | location=UK | date=5 October 2013 | accessdate=29 March 2014 }}</ref> From July 2013 to 2017 she was the President of the [[Scientific Instrument Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scientificinstrumentsociety.org/news/2017/9/17/public-lecture-silke-ackermann-20-november-2017|title=Public lecture: Silke Ackermann, 20 November 2017|work=Scientific Instrument Society|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/scientific-instruments-on-display/oclc/880237889|title=Scientific instruments on display|last=Ackermann|first=Silke|last2=Kremer|first2=Richard L|last3=Miniati|first3=Mara|date=2014|isbn=9789004264397|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://site.mast.br/sic_2017/organization.html|title=XXXVI Symposium Scientific instruments|website=site.mast.br|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> From March 2014, Ackermann has been Director of the [[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford|Museum of the History of Science]] at [[Oxford University]] and fellow of [[Linacre College, Oxford|Linacre College]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/oxfordalumni/docs/oxf10.ebook_lo/15|title=Oxford Today - Trinity Term 2014|work=Issuu|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name="oxford-times" /> taking over from the renowned and long serving Dr Jim Bennett who was succeed for 2 years by Stephen Johnston who served as the Acting Director from 2012 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/media/news_stories/2013/131004.html | title=Museum of the History of Science appoints new director | publisher=[[University of Oxford]] | location=UK | date=14 October 2013 | accessdate=29 March 2014 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004180353/http://www.ox.ac.uk/media/news_stories/2013/131004.html | archivedate=4 October 2013 | df= }}</ref> She is the first ever female head of a museum at the University of Oxford.
Ackermann's research interests include the [[history of science]] of the [[Middle Ages]] and [[Renaissance]] and the [[Islamic World]], [[scientific instruments]] (especially [[astrolabe]]s), and knowledge transfer.<ref name="archaeological">{{cite web| url=http://www.archaeological.org/lecturer/silkeackermann | title=AIA Lecturer: Silke Ackermann | publisher=[[Archaeological Institute of America]] | year=2012 | accessdate=29 March 2014 }}</ref>
